description.value: Ebony stool: the finest surviving example of its type, this stool combines precious materials and successful design with superlative craftsmanship. The leather seat dips in a double cove to give contoured support to the body from any of its four sides. Ivory inlay imitating garlands of lotus petals adorns the upper portions of the legs, contrasting brightly with the rich, dark tone of the ebony. Below the lotus garlands are miniature squares of ivory imitating through joints. The supporting lattice bracing, composed of two inner vertical struts on each side, flanked by two angled struts, is also of ivory. Stretchers of ebony terminating in ivory ferrules, which fan out in imitation of a papyrus umbel, hold the legs firmly in place. The legs taper toward the bottom and then flare out again to form a delicate, aesthetically balanced support. Incised rings ornament the tapered half.Blue glazed composition goblet in the form of a lotus flower. Three-legged wooden table; painted representation of Renenutet before offering-table and column of Hieroglyphic text on top. Acacia wood chair; back inlaid with strips of ebony and ivory flowers and points; seat of woven string; lion-paw feet. Pottery jar with cover; cream slip; painted bands of blue lotus-petal decoration; Hieroglyphic text on the shoulder. Sandal made of wood with leather strap. Sandal made of wood with leather strap.

description.value: Painted mould-made redware Egyptian goblet. Mid-to upper body sherd with an applied sprig made in a plaster mould. The sprig shows a male dancer, largely naked and balding, wearing a short belted loincloth (perhaps an animal skin), and a festive wreath, and playing double-pipes. The figure is painted an orange-red colour, with black hair, eyes, brows and wreath; there is black and white detailing on the pipes and the loincloth. The sprig may have been set in a rectangular panel, edged in brown paint. The sherd and the sprig are of a micaceous pale orange Nile silt with a few sand grains.

description.value: Painted mould-made red ware Egyptian goblet. Lower body sherd with applied sprig, the left hand part lost. Crouching naked woman with her head and visible right arm resting on a rectangular cushion, her right leg bent and her buttocks pushed out behind her. Behind her, probably in intercourse, stood a man, his right hand only surviving, seemingly holding an askos from which he pours a liquid (a perfumed oil?) onto the back of the woman. The cushion is painted red, stippled with black colour, with black hair, eyes, brows and wreath : there is black and white pipes and the loincloth. The  sprig may have been set in a rectangular pannel, edged in brown paint.The fabric is a micaceous orange brown Nile silt with some white inclusions, probably sand.

description.value: Sherd of pottery vessel. Two fragmentary mould-made relief elements applied to a wheel-made pot, probably to its neck, show a hero or possibly Ares in a shrine. A largely nude warrior stands to front, a himation hanging over his left shoulder and falling by his left side. A baldric crosses diagonally from his right shoulder, holding a sword high at his waist on his left. Both arms hang: the himation is wrapped round the left arm, and the right is poised away from his body, the hand above an object placed by his right foot. It is probably a helmet, possibly of pilos type, indicating one of the Dioskouroi, but it might be of another form, suggesting Ares. To his right and made separately, is the lower part of a fluted column on a moulded base and square plinth: presumably it was matched by another supporting the pediment of a shrine.   Micaceous orange marl clay; the hero is coated with a worn dark-red colour, probably a slip, and the column shaft is white, also likely to be a fired-on ceramic colour.

description.value: Painted mould-made redware Egyptian goblet. Lower body sherd with an applied sprig: a female figure, a goddess, wearing a long tunic, reclines on a throne. The throne had a high back (broken away) with prominent arms, supported by the front legs, the tops of which are each decorated by a small figure of a panther or lion. Drapery hangs from the seat of the throne and a flight of steps leads up to it. The goddess, perhaps holding a small pot in her left hand, is probably Euthenia or Isis (the head is lost). The sherd is decorated with black and red fired-on ceramic colours. The fabric vessel and its sprig (which was formed in a plaster mould) are of micaceous buff clay, The fabric of the pot is a micaceous buff clay, a marl ware or a marl/Nile silt mix (close to that of GR 2002.0419.1).

description.value: Sherd of pottery closed vessel body; Roman Egyptian mould-made and painted relief ware; scene of love-making. Lower body sherd with an applied sprig. The sprig was formed in a plaster mould. The relief decoration is of two lovers, naked, on a well draped bed, swagged and tasselled, with two cylindrical turned legs visible, of orange-red colour; the drapery is dark red and orange-red. The man is largely bald and the woman's hair is painted black. The man is coloured orange-red; the woman's upper part is the buff of the pot, although her visible left leg is painted dark red. An unidentified relief object appears to emerge from the man's buttocks, but is very probably the lower right leg and foot of the woman. Pencilled excavation no. inside: 96. The wall of the pot and the sprig are of the same fabric, a buff clay, perhaps a marl ware, with some mica.

description.value: Painted redware goblet. Sherd from the lower body, with an applied sprig. The sprig has been set within a metope-like area, with a lower narrow brown band and two wider "uprights" in brown paint with white dots on the edges near the relief. This relief, from the same sprig mould-series as 30, shows a young man reclining on a couch, resting his left elbow on a pillow, with his raised right arm held above his head, perhaps holding a cup, where a trace of white paint remains. He wears a himation from his waist down. The couch has a white mattress and a pillow; the himation is painted dark brown with a couple of white embellishments. His hair is black and the eyes are picked out in brown and white. Excavation Mark "HERA" incised inside. Deep orange-brown micaceous Nile silt, with a few white and many dark sand inclusions; the outer surface is paler than the inner.

description.value: Terracotta mould-made cup fragment with Isis and Bes. Part of a relief-ware cup, with a rounded body and low vertical rim. The shoulder has a series of simple gadroons and the under body has acanthus and plain rounded leaves. A central register, defined by horizontal ridges, has three figures, one almost totally lost but balanced by a dancing Bes; between them is a bust of Isis. Bes wears a short skirt and a crown of feathers. Isis has her mantle, the knot of which is just visible. She wears a closely woven wreath with ribbons on each side above it, and surmounted by a disc and cow's horns. Her hair is parted in the middle and falls in Isis-locks to her shoulders. Both arms are bent with hands raised, the right one holding a doubled garland, the left an uncertain object that emerged badly from the mould, but is probably a pot. The vessel on which these figures appear was made in a two-piece mould, the join decorated with a vertical element edged on both side with angled toothing. The outer surface and part-way down the mouth inside are covered with an orange slip. Orange-brown Nile silt, with a thin brown core, abundant fine gold mica and angular white inclusions.

Both arms are bent with hands raised, the right one holding a doubled garland, the left an uncertain object that emerged badly from the mould, but is probably a pot. The vessel on which these figures appear was made in a two-piece mould, the join decorated with a vertical element edged on both side with angled toothing. description.value: Painted mould-made redware Egyptian goblet. Upper shoulder sherd with an applied sprig set within a metope panel. The sprig, modelled largely in the round, has a male bust. The figure is shown as reclining: he may be a poet or a philosopher. He wears a himation round his shoulders and upper body, his left hand emerges from the garment and he has a forked beard. He wears a low conical cap with lappets hanging on each side. or possibly hair. Buff slip inside and reserved outside within the metope panel; the metope has surviving painted frame, most complete on the bust's proper right, with black paint partly laid over orange-red coloration, and narrow orange-red and black horizontals at the top; the vertical has a row of small white dots. Of the bust, the himalion is black with white detailing and red paint on the face and the forked beard, and on the left hand. The cap and the lappets (or hair) are black as are facial features, with white on tht eyes. Micaceous red-brown Nile silt with some white sand inclusions.

description.value: Painted mould-made redware Egyptian goblet. Lower body sherd with an applied sprig, the sprig was made in a plaster mould. Thick creamy white slip  inside and out. Standing in front of a horse or donkey, the head of which is lost, is a  man holding up a woman, who supports herself with her arms round his  neck. The man is naked and the woman wears only a short cloak; both are  engaged in mutual sexual intercourse. The horse is painted black, the man a  deep orange-brown colour; the woman's left leg and arm, and her face are  reserved in the creamy white slip. Some black paint picks out details of the  features of the woman and man and their hair, and also decorates the cloak. Dark red-brown Nile silt,  perhaps with mica and with white sand inclusions.

description.value: Great bascinet, made of iron, with a one piece skull and a possibly later front plate. The skull is pierced at the apex of the skull with a keyhole slot, possibly for the attachment of a crest. At either side of the skull is the pivoted terminal of the detachable visor. The main edges are bordered by close set lining holes, and round the base of the skull is a row of lining rivet holes. The front plate has a row of flush lining rivets at its lower edge. At the lower rear is a group of three rivets above a large hole, for a lost hinged hasp for securing the helmet to the backplate. The surface is patinated. The front plate is damaged at the edges, and somewhat dented.
